721725f-a.text:
Morningside Park: A set of two views forming a panorama of the southerly portion of same which is bounded in these views by Cathedral Parkway (foreground, not seen), Manhattan Ave. (right) and Morningside Drive (left). Forking off Manhattan Ave. at West 114th Street is Morningside Ave. to continue the easterly boundary of the Park. Atop the bluff at the left is the Cathedral of St. John (Protestant Episcopal) in a skeletal state. North of same are the 8 story structures of St. Luke's Hospital. The photographer's vantage point is the 110th Street station of the Ninth Ave. Elevated line and is viewing northwestward.
March 1906.
George L. Balgue.

721718f-a.text:
Morningside Drive, between Cathedral Parkway and 112th Street, looking northwest, showing the Cathedral of St. John the Divine, and Choir School at the left. In the next block north is St. Luke's Hospital.
About 1925

721720f-a.text:
Morningside Drive, west side, from Cathedral Parkway, (West 110th Street), to and including 113th Street. At the right of the picture is the Protestant Episcopal Cathedral of St. John the Devine, (A rear view). This view also shows Cathedral Parkway (110th Street), north side, from and including Morningside Drive, to and including Amsterdam Ave.
1926.
Brown Brothers.

718118f-b.text:
Cathedral Parkway (W. 110th Street) at Manhattan Avenue, showing details of the 9th Avenue 'El' system and its station at this point. The photographer's general direction is westward. The tracks curve southward at Columbus Avenue, and the Parkway continues uphill towards Amsterdam Avenue and Broadway. Morningside Park is on the right with the Protestant Cathedral of St. John just beyond. Note the glimpse of St. Lukes Hospital over the station shedroof.
June 6, 1940
Views 1,2,3
P. L. Sperr

721719f-a.text:
Morningside Drive, between Cathedral Parkway and 113th Street, view northwest from the Ninth Avenue Elevated station. This shows the choir school, the old part of the Cathedral of St. John the Divine, with the new nave under construction, and St. Luke's
Hospital on the northern side of 112th Street.
October 25, 1927.
